nce of Color Perception and Climate Change -- t11. Color and Sexual Deception in Orchids: Progress toward Understanding the Functions and Pollinator Perception of Floral Color -- t12. Impacts of Extreme Weather Spells on Flowering Phenology of Wild Orchids in Guangxi, Southwestern China -- tSummary -- tReferences -- tList of Contributors -- tTaxonomic Index -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor biologists, 2009 was an epochal year: the bicentennial of Charles Darwin’s birth and the 150th anniversary of the publication of a book now known simply as The Origin of Species. But for many botanists, Darwin’s true legacy starts with the 1862 publication of another volume: On the Various Contrivances by Which British and Foreign Orchids Are Fertilised by Insects and on the Good Effects of Intercrossing, or Fertilisation of Orchids. This slim but detailed book with the improbably long title was the first in a series of plant studies by Darwin that continues to serve as a global exemplar in the field of evolutionary botany. In Darwin’s Orchids, an international group of orchid biologists unites to celebrate and explore the continuum that stretches from Darwin’s groundbreaking orchid research to that of today. Mirroring the structure of Fertilisation of Orchids, Darwin’s Orchids investigates flowers from Darwin’s home in England, through the southern hemisphere, and on to North America and China as it seeks to address a set of questions first put forward by Darwin himself: What pollinates this particular type of orchid? How does its pollination mechanism work? Will an orchid self-pollinate or is an insect or other animal vector required? And how has this orchid’s lineage changed over time? Diverse in their colors, forms, aromas, and pollination schemes, orchids have long been considered ideal models for the study of plant evolution and conservation. Looking to the past, present, and future of botany, Darwin’s Orchids will be a vital addition to this tradition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBotanyxHistory. 0aOrchids. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aeducation, college, university, academic, scholarly, textbook, research, analysis, professor, essay collection, anthology, biology, biologists, science, scientific community, scientist, 2009, bicentennial, origin of species, discovery, theory, fertilisation, flowers, plant studies, plants, flora, botany, evolutionary, evolution, international, england, southern hemisphere, global, pollinators, pollinating, hypothesis, conservation, gardens.1 aBernhardt, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernhardt, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aClements, Mark A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCozzolino, Salvatore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDafni, Amots, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeng, Zheng-Hai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdens-Meier, Retha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdens-Meier, Retha, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFeng, Chang-Lin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFournel, Jacques, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrancisco, Ana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaskett, A. C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIndsto, James O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Steven D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLin, Wuying, econtributor.